        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "# Welcome back, James \uD83D\uDC4B\n\nFirst — the fact that you've stayed patient through this injury and worked with your physio to get cleared? That's exactly the kind of discipline that builds durable runners. You've got a solid foundation to return to, and we're going to protect it.\n\nBefore I walk you through the full plan, I want to make sure it actually fits your life. **What does \"getting back\" mean to you right now?** Is it simply moving without pain again, rebuilding toward that 44:00 10K, or something else? There's no wrong answer — it'll just help me frame how we talk about progress together.\n\nIn the meantime, here's your full return-to-running plan. I've built it around what your physio has cleared, your training history, and what the evidence says about returning safely from plantar fasciitis.\n\n---\n\n## A Few Things You Should Know Before We Start\n\n**Your paces come from your pre-injury 10K of 44:00 (VDOT 46.5).** Because you've had some deconditioning, your easy pace is your only tool right now — and that's genuinely okay. Easy running isn't \"less than\" real training. It's where aerobic adaptation happens, where tendons recover, and where you rebuild the foundation that fast running is built on. Your physiotherapist has cleared you for **easy running only, up to 20 minutes**, with walking breaks if you feel any foot pain.\n\n**What \"easy\" actually means:** 5:24–5:58/km. If that feels too fast on any given day, go slower. The lower end of easy is still excellent training.\n\n**One rule I'll ask you to honor above all others:** foot pain is a stop sign, not a suggestion. Any foot pain → walking break immediately. Persistent pain across a session → end the run and let me know.\n\n---\n\n## Plan Overview\n\n| Phase | Duration | Focus | Weekly Volume |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Phase 1 | Weeks 1–3 | Re-establish tolerance | ~10–12 km |\n| Phase 2 | Weeks 4–6 | Build confidence & consistency | ~12–15 km |\n| Phase 3 | Weeks 7–9 | Consolidate base | ~15–18 km |\n| Deload | Week 4 & Week 8 | Recovery & adaptation | ~8–10 km |\n\n**3 days/week maximum. Long run on Saturday. All runs easy pace (5:24–5:58/km). No speed work until physiotherapist clears you.**\n\n---\n\n## Phase 1 — Re-establishing Tolerance (Weeks 1–3)\n\n*The goal here is simple: prove to your foot that running is safe. We're not chasing fitness. We're earning trust.*\n\n### Week 1\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 15 min @ 5:40–5:58/km · Walk break at 7–8 min if any discomfort |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 15 min @ 5:40–5:58/km · Walk break at 7–8 min if any discomfort |\n| Saturday | Long Run | 20 min @ 5:45–5:58/km · Walk the last 5 min if foot feels fatigued |\n\n**Week 1 Target: ~9–10 km**\n\n> \uD83E\uDDE0 **Why this volume?** Your most recent full week was 8.9 km across 3 runs. Starting near there — not below, not dramatically above — respects where you actually are while honoring the 10% progression rule.\n\n---\n\n### Week 2\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 18 min @ 5:35–5:55/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 18 min @ 5:35–5:55/km |\n| Saturday | Long Run | 20 min @ 5:40–5:58/km |\n\n**Week 2 Target: ~10.5–11 km**\n\n---\n\n### Week 3\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:30–5:50/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:30–5:50/km |\n| Saturday | Long Run | 20 min @ 5:35–5:55/km |\n\n**Week 3 Target: ~11.5–12 km**\n\n> ✅ **Phase 1 milestone:** By the end of Week 3, you're running 20 minutes three times a week with no persistent foot pain. That's the signal to move forward.\n\n---\n\n## Deload — Week 4\n\n*Every 3–4 weeks, we pull back intentionally. This isn't going backward — it's when your body actually absorbs the training.*\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 15 min @ 5:45–5:58/km · Easy and relaxed |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 15 min @ 5:45–5:58/km |\n| Saturday | Long Run | 20 min @ 5:45–5:58/km |\n\n**Week 4 Target: ~8–9 km**\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2 — Building Confidence & Consistency (Weeks 5–7)\n\n*Now that your foot has tolerated consistent easy running, we start extending duration modestly. The 20-minute cap lifts gradually as you report how things feel.*\n\n> ⚠️ **Important:** The duration increases below assume your foot pain has remained absent or minimal through Phase 1. If you've had ongoing discomfort, we hold at 20 minutes and check back in with your physio before proceeding.\n\n### Week 5\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 22 min @ 5:30–5:50/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 22 min @ 5:30–5:50/km |\n| Saturday | Long Run | 25 min @ 5:35–5:55/km |\n\n**Week 5 Target: ~12.5–13.5 km**\n\n---\n\n### Week 6\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 25 min @ 5:28–5:48/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 25 min @ 5:28–5:48/km |\n| Saturday | Long Run | 30 min @ 5:35–5:55/km |\n\n**Week 6 Target: ~14–15 km**\n\n---\n\n### Week 7\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 28 min @ 5:26–5:46/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 28 min @ 5:26–5:46/km |\n| Saturday | Long Run | 35 min @ 5:35–5:55/km |\n\n**Week 7 Target: ~15.5–16.5 km**\n\n> ✅ **Phase 2 milestone:** You're completing 35-minute long runs with no foot pain flare-ups. You might also want to check back in with your physiotherapist here — this is a natural evaluation point for discussing return to speed work.\n\n---\n\n## Deload — Week 8\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:40–5:58/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:40–5:58/km |\n| Saturday | Long Run | 25 min @ 5:40–5:58/km |\n\n**Week 8 Target: ~10–11 km**\n\n---\n\n## Phase 3 — Consolidating the Base (Weeks 9–11)\n\n*This phase locks in your new baseline and prepares you for the next chapter — whether that's a goal race, structured training, or simply running confidently again.*\n\n### Week 9\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 30 min @ 5:26–5:46/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 30 min @ 5:26–5:46/km |\n| Saturday | Long Run | 40 min @ 5:30–5:50/km |\n\n**Week 9 Target: ~17–18 km**\n\n---\n\n### Week 10\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 32 min @ 5:24–5:44/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 32 min @ 5:24–5:44/km |\n| Saturday | Long Run | 45 min @ 5:30–5:50/km |\n\n**Week 10 Target: ~18.5–19.5 km**\n\n---\n\n### Week 11\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy Run | 35 min @ 5:24–5:44/km |\n| Thursday | Easy Run | 35 min @ 5:24–5:44/km |\n| Saturday | Long Run | 50 min @ 5:30–5:50/km |\n\n**Week 11 Target: ~20–21 km**\n\n> ✅ **Phase 3 milestone:** A 50-minute long run, three times per week, no foot pain. At this point, with physiotherapist clearance, you're genuinely ready to introduce structured training — strides, tempo, whatever direction you want to go.\n\n---\n\n## A Few Things Worth Keeping in Mind\n\n**Foot pain protocol — every run:**\n- Mild discomfort in the first 5 minutes that fades? That's common with PF. Keep going cautiously.\n- Pain that builds during the run? Take a walking break. If it continues, end the session.\n- Pain that lingers after the run or into the next morning? Contact your physio before your next run.\n\n**What you're *not* doing yet — and why that's smart:**\nThreshold, interval, and repetition paces are in your profile (4:29, 4:12, 3:57/km). Those aren't being ignored — they're being protected. Tendons and fascia adapt more slowly than cardiovascular fitness. Running easy now means those faster sessions actually work when we get there.\n\n**On the days you're not running:**\nLight walking, mobility work, and your physio's prescribed foot exercises will complement this plan meaningfully. If you're doing calf raises or foot strengthening — keep it up. That work is directly protecting this plan.\n\n---\n\n## What Comes Next\n\nOnce you reach the end of Week 11 with consistent, pain-free running, you'll have rebuilt a genuine base. At that point, we can talk about:\n- A structured 10K build toward or beyond your 44:00 PR\n- Introducing quality sessions with physiotherapist clearance\n- A longer-term race goal if that interests you\n\n---\n\n**One question to close on:** As you look at this plan, what feels realistic and what — if anything — feels like it might be a stretch given your current day-to-day? I'd rather adjust now than have you quietly grinding through something that doesn't fit. \uD83D\uDE42"
        }
